.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-1----
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-2-title: Feature Catalog Common Pitfalls
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md:3:description: Deep-dive on recurring feature-catalog defects with worked before/after fixes, plus the template-versus-reference split for the catalog package.
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-4-trigger_phrases:
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-5-  - "feature catalog pitfalls"
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-6-  - "feature catalog common mistakes"
--
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-36-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-37-### Renaming published slugs
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-38-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md:39:**Symptom**: A category folder or per-feature filename is renamed after other docs already link to it.
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-40-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md:41:**Why it breaks**: Playbooks, READMEs, and specs link to catalog paths. A rename silently breaks every inbound link, and CI catches it only if those links live in checked markdown.
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-42-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-43-**Fix**: Treat slugs as an API. Stabilize category names, feature names, and slugs *before* polishing prose, and keep them fixed after publication. If a rename is genuinely required, do it as a deliberate migration that updates every referrer in the same change.
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-44-
--
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-56-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-57-**Why it breaks**: That is a manual testing playbook's job. Mixing it in blurs the boundary and bloats the inventory the catalog is supposed to keep scannable.
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-58-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md:59:**Fix**: Keep execution matrices in the playbook. In the catalog, describe *what* the behavior is and link to the playbook for *how to validate it*. See the catalog/playbook boundary in `SKILL.md`.
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-60-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-61-### Playbook cross-references drifting from catalog names
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-62-
--
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-74-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-75-**Fix**: Once the section exceeds three paragraphs, break it into H3 sub-headings — `### Core Behavior`, `### Configuration`, `### Edge Cases`, `### Async & Safety`. Short sections stay plain prose; the rule triggers only on length. The live `unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md` file shows this applied well.
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-76-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md:77:### Missing trigger_phrases in frontmatter
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-78-
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/common-pitfalls.md-79-**Symptom**: A per-feature file ships without a `trigger_phrases` list.
