    13	---
    14	
    15	# Skill-Benchmark Storage Guide
    16	
    17	Where a Lane C skill-benchmark run's artifacts live, how the run-label folders
    18	are named, and which of those artifacts is machine-owned. This is a storage and
    19	naming standard only. It does NOT restate the measurement contract: the
    20	five-dimension (D1-D5) computation, point weights, verdict bands, funnel, and
    21	advisory signals live once in the deep-improvement scoring authority, linked in
    22	section 1 and section 6. Where this guide and that contract diverge, the contract
    23	prevails.
    24	
    25	---
    26	
    27	## 1. OVERVIEW
    28	
    29	A **skill-benchmark** measures whether a skill is well-routed, discoverable,
    30	efficient, and useful in practice. It is run by the deep-improvement **Lane C**
    31	harness (`/deep:skill-benchmark`) and emits a dual JSON+Markdown report per run.
    32	This guide governs one thing: **where those reports are stored and how the folders
    33	are named**, so a future engineer can find every run for a skill beside the skill
    34	it measures.
    35	
    36	The convention is: each benchmarked skill or hub carries a `benchmark/` directory,
    37	and every run of the Lane C harness writes its report pair into its own
    38	**`<run-label>/`** subfolder inside that `benchmark/` tree. Runs are siblings; one
    39	run never overwrites another. One run-label — conventionally `baseline/` — is the
    40	**frozen** comparison anchor and is never regenerated.
    41	
    42	This guide is normative for storage and naming only. Two deep-improvement-owned
    43	documents remain the authority for everything the reports contain:
    44	
    45	| Concern | Authority (owned by deep-improvement) |
    46	| --- | --- |
    47	| D1-D5 computation, point weights, Mode A/B scoring, advisory signals, funnel/bottleneck ranking | [`scoring-contract.md`](../../../../system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/references/skill-benchmark/scoring-contract.md) |
    48	| How to run Lane C, invocation flags, dimension coverage, verdict bands, target eligibility | [`operator-guide.md`](../../../../system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/references/skill-benchmark/operator-guide.md) |
    49	
    50	Do not copy either contract into this packet. Cross-link them.
    51	
    52	### Live examples in the wild
    53	
    54	Read these two shipped hub trees to see the convention filled in against real
    55	skills:
    56	
    57	- [`system-deep-loop/benchmark/README.md`](../../../../system-deep-loop/benchmark/README.md) — a hub benchmarking itself with the harness that lives inside it.
    58	- [`sk-code/benchmark/README.md`](../../../../sk-code/benchmark/README.md) — a hub with the fullest set of run-label folders, its structure and reading guide.
    59	
    60	---
    61	
    62	## 2. THE HUB benchmark/ TREE
    63	
    64	A hub `benchmark/` tree holds an optional index plus one folder per run:
    65	
    66	```text
    67	<skill-or-hub>/benchmark/
    68	├── README.md                     # optional hub index (verdict, structure, how to re-run)
    69	├── baseline/                     # FROZEN anchor — the before-snapshot, never regenerated
    70	│   ├── skill-benchmark-report.json
    71	│   └── skill-benchmark-report.md
    72	├── router-final/                 # a run-label folder (one Lane C run)
    73	│   ├── skill-benchmark-report.json
    74	│   └── skill-benchmark-report.md
    75	├── live-final/                   # another run-label folder
    76	│   ├── skill-benchmark-report.json
    77	│   └── skill-benchmark-report.md
    78	└── fixtures/                     # optional INPUT corpus — not a run, holds no report
    79	```
    80	
    81	| Entry | What it is |
    82	| --- | --- |
    83	| `benchmark/` | The per-skill benchmark root, kept beside the skill it measures |
    84	| `benchmark/README.md` | Optional hub index — the look-here-first surface: current verdict, folder map, and re-run command. A `benchmark/` root README is a `readme`-type doc and may be templated |
    85	| `benchmark/<run-label>/` | One Lane C run. Sibling to every other run; never overwrites another |
    86	| `benchmark/baseline/` | The frozen comparison anchor. Do not regenerate or overwrite it — a new run is always a new sibling folder |
    87	| `benchmark/fixtures/` | Optional input corpus (public/private fixture pairs). An input, not a run — it holds no `skill-benchmark-report.*` pair |
    88	
    89	**The frozen-baseline rule.** `baseline/` is the pre-optimization snapshot every
    90	later run is compared against. Regenerating it destroys the anchor, so it is
    91	never re-run in place. Add each new run as a sibling (`router-final/`, `after-*/`,
    92	a model-stamped `live-*/`, and so on).
    93	
    94	---
    95	
    96	## 3. RUN-LABEL NAMING
    97	
    98	New run-label folders are named by **trace mode plus purpose** and match
    99	`^[a-z0-9]+(?:-[a-z0-9]+)*$`. Existing underscore folders in shipped hub trees
   100	remain historical references until their owning rename phase. The label is a
   101	human convenience; the run's authoritative parameters live inside its
   102	`skill-benchmark-report.json`.
   103	
   104	| Run-label pattern | Meaning |
   105	| --- | --- |
   106	| `baseline/` | The frozen pre-optimization snapshot and comparison anchor (see section 2). |
   107	| `router-mode-a/`, `router-final/`, `router-baseline/` | Router-mode (Mode A) runs — deterministic, offline router-replay; the CI gate. |
   108	| `live-mode-b/`, `live-final/`, `live/`, `live-remediated/` | Live-mode (Mode B) runs — real dispatch through `cli-opencode` to a model. |
   109	| `after/`, `after-d3-proxy/`, `after-<change-tag>/` | Post-change runs compared against `baseline/`; the tag names the change or milestone the run measures. |
   110	| `d4r-live/` | An opt-in D4-R task-outcome (usefulness) ablation run. |
   111	| `full/` | A full-coverage run over the whole scenario corpus. |
   112	| `live-<model>-<variant>/` | A live run stamped with the executor model and reasoning variant it dispatched through (for example a GLM or Kimi leg). |
   113	
   114	Trace-mode semantics (router vs live) and the flags that produce each run are
   115	owned by [`operator-guide.md`](../../../../system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/references/skill-benchmark/operator-guide.md);
   116	this guide only fixes how the resulting folder is named and where it sits.
   117	
   118	---
   119	
   120	## 4. WHAT LANDS IN A RUN-LABEL DIR
   121	
   122	Every run writes a **matched report pair** and nothing else, unless a per-run
   123	`README.md` note was authored by hand. There is no separate `d4-ablation.json` or
   124	`d5-connectivity-detail.json` artifact: an opt-in `--d4` (D4-R task-outcome) run
   125	rewrites the SAME `skill-benchmark-report.json` / `.md` pair in place rather than
   126	writing a sibling file, and D5's structural-connectivity result is a field inside
   127	`skill-benchmark-report.json`, not a standalone detail file (verify against
   128	`run-skill-benchmark.cjs`).
   129	
   130	| File | Required | Content |
   131	| --- | --- | --- |
   132	| `skill-benchmark-report.json` | Yes | The machine report: verdict, D1-D5 dimension scores, funnel, ranked bottlenecks, and per-scenario rows. The canonical artifact. An opt-in `--d4` D4-R run rewrites this same file in place. |
   133	| `skill-benchmark-report.md` | Yes | The same report rendered for reading, generated FROM the JSON. Renderer-owned — see section 5. |
   134	| `README.md` | Optional | A short per-run note (context for a one-off or model-stamped leg). |
   135	
   136	Read order: open `skill-benchmark-report.md` for the verdict and the ranked
   137	bottlenecks; open `skill-benchmark-report.json` for per-scenario detail and for
   138	any diff against `baseline/skill-benchmark-report.json`.
   139	
   140	---
   141	
   142	## 5. BOUNDARY: THE REPORT .md IS RENDERER-OWNED
   143	
   144	**`skill-benchmark-report.md` is a machine render. Never hand-author or hand-edit
   145	it.** It is produced solely by the deep-improvement renderer
   146	[`build-report.cjs`](../../../../system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/build-report.cjs),
   147	which renders the Markdown FROM `skill-benchmark-report.json` specifically so the
   148	two artifacts cannot drift. That renderer is the ONLY writer of the report `.md`;
   149	it takes the report object, not score arguments.
   150	
   151	The consequences of this boundary:
   152	
   153	| Rule | Why |
   154	| --- | --- |
   155	| Do not edit `skill-benchmark-report.md` by hand | It is an anti-drift render of the JSON. A hand edit desynchronizes it from its source of truth and is silently overwritten on the next run. |
   156	| Do not author a fill-in template for `skill-benchmark-report.md` | There is no authoring template for a rendered report. To change the report, change the JSON the run emits or the renderer, both owned by deep-improvement. Templates in this packet are for the hub `benchmark/README.md` index and for INPUT fixtures/profiles only. |
   157	| Do not copy the D1-D5 scoring, reviewer schema, or any scorer/runner into this packet | The scoring contract, reviewer schema, and the runner/renderer scripts are lane-local to deep-improvement. Cross-link them; never relocate them. |
   158	
   159	To correct a report: fix the input (fixtures/router/scenario gold) or the scorer,
   160	then re-run Lane C so the renderer regenerates the pair. Never patch the `.md`.
   161	
   162	---
   163	
   164	## 6. RELATED RESOURCES
   165	
   166	### Normative contract (owned by deep-improvement — link, do not restate)
   167	
   168	- [`scoring-contract.md`](../../../../system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/references/skill-benchmark/scoring-contract.md) — the authoritative D1-D5 computation: point weights, Mode A deterministic scoring, the opt-in advisor probe, live-mode dimensions, advisory signals, and funnel/bottleneck ranking.
   169	- [`operator-guide.md`](../../../../system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/references/skill-benchmark/operator-guide.md) — how to run Lane C: invocation, flags, dimension coverage, verdict bands, and target eligibility.
   170	- [`scenario-authoring.md`](../../../../system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/references/skill-benchmark/scenario-authoring.md) — how to author the Lane C scenarios and fixture corpus a run scores; the doctrine for the optional `benchmark/fixtures/` input pairs.
   171	- [`build-report.cjs`](../../../../system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/build-report.cjs) — the renderer that owns `skill-benchmark-report.md` (see section 5).
   172	- [`/deep:skill-benchmark`](../../../../../commands/deep/skill-benchmark.md) — the command that drives a Lane C run.
   173	
   174	### Shipped hub trees to model against
   175	
   176	- [`system-deep-loop/benchmark/README.md`](../../../../system-deep-loop/benchmark/README.md) — a hub benchmark index and run-label set.
   177	- [`sk-code/benchmark/README.md`](../../../../sk-code/benchmark/README.md) — the fullest run-label set with a structure and reading guide.
   178	
   179	### Within this packet
   180	
   181	- [`../SKILL.md`](../../SKILL.md) — the create-benchmark workflow and report contracts.
   182	- [`README.md`](../shared/README.md) — the benchmark-creation reference map.
   183	- [`behavior-benchmark-guide.md`](../behavior-benchmark/behavior-benchmark-guide.md) — authoring guide for the distinct behavior-benchmark family (executor behavior at a deep-loop mode's invocation surface), not the Lane C skill-benchmark storage covered here.
   184	- [`create-manual-testing-playbook`](../../../create-manual-testing-playbook/SKILL.md) — the sibling sk-doc skill that authors a manual-testing scenario corpus; hand its corpus into the optional `benchmark/fixtures/` input pairs when a Lane C run scores against curated scenarios rather than live discovery.
   185	
   186	---
   187	
   188	*End of skill-benchmark storage guide — the normative D1-D5 measurement contract lives in [`scoring-contract.md`](../../../../system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/references/skill-benchmark/scoring-contract.md), owned by deep-improvement.*
