   339	## 6. VALIDATION AND RELEASE GATES
   340	
   341	### Automated Checks
   342	
   343	Run shared validation on the root playbook before delivery from the repo root (replace `<SKILL_PATH>` with the target skill directory, e.g. `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit`):
   344	
   345	```bash
   346	# New-content naming guard. The staging root must contain only the newly authored
   347	# canonical manual-testing-playbook package, never an ancestor with shipped legacy roots.
   348	python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/check_no_hyphenated_catalog_content.py <new-content-staging-root>
   349	
   350	python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py <SKILL_PATH>/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md --type reference
   351	python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/extract_structure.py <SKILL_PATH>/manual-testing-playbook/manual-testing-playbook.md
   352	```
   353	
   354	The staging scope is mandatory until shipped underscore roots are migrated. Do not run this guard against `.opencode/skills` or another ancestor containing legacy `feature_catalog/` or `manual_testing_playbook/` trees.
   355	
   356	Also check:
   357	
   358	- Broken local links, by grep/script or the repository markdown-link guard.
   359	- Feature ID counts between the root index and per-feature files.
   360	- Automated-test links, when referenced.
   361	- Feature-catalog links, when referenced.
   362	
   363	### Manual Checks
   364	
   365	The current validator is root-document focused. It does not recurse into category folders and does not prove every cross-file playbook link by itself. Cross-file markdown links are covered separately by the `check-markdown-links.cjs` CI guard, which verifies every markdown link across skills, commands, and agents and fails the PR on a broken link; per-feature file structure inside the category folders still needs manual review.
   382	## 7. RULES
   383	
   384	### ✅ ALWAYS
   385	
   386	1. Use `manual-testing-playbook.md` as the root file name.
   387	2. Put per-feature files in root-level category folders named with the bare descriptive slug.
   388	3. Keep one canonical per-feature file for each feature ID.
   389	4. Use exact prompts, exact command sequences, observable expected signals, captured evidence, and binary pass/fail criteria.
   390	5. Keep shared review, orchestration, and release-readiness rules in the root playbook.
   391	6. Link scenarios back to the matching feature catalog entry when a catalog exists.
   392	7. Explicitly document exceptions when no matching catalog entry exists.
   393	8. Mark destructive scenarios and include safe recovery expectations.
   394	9. Validate the root playbook and manually review per-feature files before delivery.
   395	
   396	### ⛔ NEVER
   397	
   398	1. Create a `snippets/` subtree for canonical per-feature files.
   399	2. Create separate canonical `review_protocol.md` or `subagent_utilization_ledger.md` files.
   400	3. Duplicate full execution truth in the root summary.
   401	4. Renumber published feature IDs just to remove gaps.
   402	5. Use packet-history or spec-phase references as scenario identity.
   403	6. Ship unsynchronized prompt fields.
   404	7. Add packet-local `graph-metadata.json`.
   405	8. Add numeric prefixes to category folder names or per-feature filenames; the root playbook index owns display order and the per-feature `stage:` field owns benchmark tier.
   406	9. Never use underscores in category folder or per-feature filename path segments.
   407	
   408	### ⚠️ ESCALATE IF
   409	
   410	1. The target feature set, category boundary, or package owner is unclear.
   411	2. A scenario would require destructive actions without a safe recovery path.
   412	3. The user expects external credentials, live production access, or privileged tool execution.
   413	4. Feature catalog links are required but no stable catalog exists.
   414	5. Validation fails after structural fixes.
   415	6. The requested package shape conflicts with existing published playbooks.
   416	
   417	---
   418	
   419	## 8. SUCCESS CRITERIA
   420	
   421	A `create-manual-testing-playbook` run is done when:
   422	
   423	- The package uses the canonical shape: root `manual-testing-playbook.md` plus kebab-case category folders of per-feature files, with no `snippets/` subtree and no separate `review_protocol.md` or `subagent_utilization_ledger.md`.
   424	- Every feature ID maps to exactly one per-feature file, and no packet-local `graph-metadata.json` was added.
   425	- Every scenario is deterministic: exact prompt, exact command sequence, observable expected signals, captured evidence, and binary `PASS`/`FAIL`/`SKIP` verdicts.
   426	- Prompt fields are synchronized across the scenario contract, the execution table, and any root summary.
   427	- Destructive scenarios are marked and isolated with safe recovery expectations.
   428	- The root playbook passes shared `validate_document.py`, per-feature files are manually spot-checked, and any remaining manual scope is documented honestly.
   429	
   430	---

